<%#
  # Partial: _normative_article_entry.html.erb
  # Date: 03/26/2026
  # Author: Moisés Reis
  # Package: Meta
  #
  # Description: Renders a single PortfolioNormativeArticle row inside the portfolio form.
  #              Shows a dropdown for choosing an article and, once a selection is made,
  #              reveals three numeric inputs for the portfolio-side benchmark, minimum,
  #              and maximum targets that will be compared against the article's own values.
  #
  # Usage:: - What: One self-contained row representing a PortfolioNormativeArticle join record.
  #         - How:  The entry div listens for bubbled change events from its child select so the
  #                 Stimulus controller can reveal the target inputs without needing to modify
  #                 the _select partial. A hidden _destroy field lets Rails soft-delete the
  #                 record when the user removes the row without a full page reload.
  #         - Why:  Keeping the row in its own partial allows the <template> in
  #                 _normative_articles_fieldset to pre-render a blank version server-side,
  #                 which the Stimulus controller clones for new additions at runtime.
  #
  # Locals:: - f                   [ActionView::Helpers::FormBuilder]
  #               The nested fields_for builder scoped to PortfolioNormativeArticle.
  #          - normative_articles  [Array<Array>]
  #               Collection of [display_name, id] pairs for the select options.
  %>

<%# Explanation:: This wrapper div is the boundary of a single article entry. The
  #               data-target marks it so the controller can traverse up to it from
  #               any child element. The delegated data-action on this div catches
  #               change events that bubble up from the nested _select partial, which
  #               means the _select partial itself does not need to be modified.
  %>
<<<<<<< HEAD
<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 p-6 border border-border rounded-base bg-white w-full"
=======
<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 p-6 border border-border rounded-base bg-background w-full"
>>>>>>> d053dcf (fix: incorrect info in portfolio PDF and UI overhaul)
     data-nested-normative-articles-target="entry"
     data-action="change->nested-normative-articles#onSelectChange">

  <div class="flex flex-row justify-start items-center">

    <%# Explanation:: This button marks the row for removal. For persisted records it sets
      #               the hidden _destroy field to "1" and hides the row so Rails destroys
      #               the join record on the next save. For brand-new rows it removes the
      #               DOM node entirely because no database record exists yet.
      %>
    <button type="button"
            class="button button-icon button-small button-danger"
            data-action="click->nested-normative-articles#removeEntry"
            title="Remover artigo">
      <%= inline_svg_tag "icons/x.svg" %>
    </button>
  </div>

  <%# Explanation:: This row holds the article selector and the remove button side by side.
    #               The selector is flex-grow so it occupies all available horizontal space
    #               while the remove button stays fixed at its intrinsic width.
    %>
  <div class="flex flex-row items-start justify-between gap-4">

    <%# Explanation:: This select renders the dropdown of all existing NormativeArticle records.
      #               It uses the standard _select partial to inherit tom-select behaviour,
      #               consistent label styling, and built-in error display. The native change
      #               event fired by tom-select bubbles up to the entry div above.
      %>
    <div class="w-full">
      <%= render "partials/modules/select",
                 f: f,
                 name: :normative_article_id,
                 label: "Artigo Normativo",
                 desc: "Selecione o artigo a ser aplicado a esta carteira.",
                 options_collection: [["Escolha um artigo normativo", ""]] + normative_articles,
                 selected: f.object.normative_article_id
      %>
    </div>
  </div>

  <%# Explanation:: These three inputs are hidden until the user selects an article. The
    #               conditional CSS class checks the persisted normative_article_id so that
    #               on edit the inputs are immediately visible for already-linked articles.
    #               The Stimulus controller toggles the hidden class when the select changes.
    %>
  <div class="<%= f.object.normative_article_id.present? ? '' : 'hidden' %> grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3"
       data-nested-normative-articles-target="targets">

    <%# Explanation:: This field captures the portfolio-side benchmark to compare against
      #               the article's own benchmark_target value in compliance reporting.
      %>
    <%= render "partials/modules/input-field",
               f: f,
               name: :benchmark_target,
               label: "Benchmark Target",
               placeholder: "0.00",
               desc: "Meta de benchmark desta carteira.",
               field_type: :number_field,
               icon_name: "target",
               step: :any
    %>

    <%# Explanation:: This field records the minimum allocation or return threshold the
      #               portfolio must meet relative to this article's minimum_target.
      %>
    <%= render "partials/modules/input-field",
               f: f,
               name: :minimum_target,
               label: "Meta Mínima",
               placeholder: "0.00",
               desc: "Percentual mínimo permitido.",
               field_type: :number_field,
               icon_name: "trending-down",
               step: :any
    %>

    <%# Explanation:: This field stores the upper bound the portfolio must not exceed,
      #               mirroring the article's own maximum_target for the comparison.
      %>
    <%= render "partials/modules/input-field",
               f: f,
               name: :maximum_target,
               label: "Meta Máxima",
               placeholder: "100.00",
               desc: "Percentual máximo permitido.",
               field_type: :number_field,
               icon_name: "trending-up",
               step: :any
    %>
  </div>

  <%# Explanation:: This hidden field is the Rails convention for nested-form deletion.
    #               When the controller sets its value to "1" the record is destroyed on save,
    #               provided the parent model has allow_destroy: true in its
    #               accepts_nested_attributes_for declaration.
    %>
  <%= f.hidden_field :_destroy,
                     value: "0",
                     data: { "nested-normative-articles-target": "destroy" }
  %>

</div>
